\subsection{Fast-Slow Decomposition}
\label{subsec:fast_slow_decomposition}

To isolate the rapid subgrid-scale turbulent relaxation from the slower evolution of the macroscale atmospheric flow and land surface temperature, we introduce the formal singular perturbation parameter $0 < \varepsilon \ll 1$. By scaling time relative to the slow macroscopic processes, the coupled SBL system can be rigorously cast into a standard GSPT fast-slow framework:

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\varepsilon \frac{de}{dt} &= \mathcal{F}(e, \mathbf{y}; \varepsilon), \\
\frac{d\mathbf{y}}{dt} &= \mathcal{G}(e, \mathbf{y}; \varepsilon),
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:gspt_abstract_form}
\end{equation}

where $e$ serves as the fast coordinate representing the turbulent kinetic energy (TKE), and $\mathbf{y} = (U, V, T_s)^T \in \mathbb{R}^3$ represents the vector of slow state variables. The explicit forms of the fast vector field $\mathcal{F}$ and slow vector field $\mathcal{G}$ map directly to the prognostic physical equations detailed in Section~\ref{subsec:mathematical_fast_slow}.

This formulation ensures that in the singular limit $\varepsilon \to 0$, the turbulent states are constrained to an invariant manifold where production balances dissipation instantaneously, while the slow variables dictate the secular drift of the entire system across phase space.